🟢 Strategy Pattern — Notes
🧠 1️⃣ Definition

Strategy Pattern defines a family of algorithms (behaviors), encapsulates each one, and makes them interchangeable at runtime.

🎯 2️⃣ Problem It Solves
❌ Without Strategy
class PaymentService {

    public void pay(String type, int amount) {

        if(type.equals("UPI")) {
            System.out.println("Pay via UPI");
        }
        else if(type.equals("CARD")) {
            System.out.println("Pay via Card");
        }
    }
}
Problems

Too many if/switch ❌

Hard to extend ❌

Violates Open/Closed Principle ❌

Logic becomes messy ❌

✅ 3️⃣ Strategy Solution

👉 Move each behavior into separate classes

🧱 4️⃣ Structure
1️⃣ Strategy Interface
interface PaymentStrategy {
    void pay(int amount);
}
2️⃣ Concrete Strategies
class UpiPaymentStrategy implements PaymentStrategy {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid via UPI");
    }
}
class CardPaymentStrategy implements PaymentStrategy {
    public void pay(int amount) {
        System.out.println("Paid via Card");
    }
}
3️⃣ Context (Main Class)
class PaymentService {

    private PaymentStrategy strategy;

    public PaymentService(PaymentStrategy strategy) {
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    public void pay(int amount) {
        strategy.pay(amount);
    }
}
4️⃣ Usage
PaymentService service = new PaymentService(new UpiPaymentStrategy());
service.pay(100);
🔁 5️⃣ Runtime Behavior Change
PaymentService service = new PaymentService(new CardPaymentStrategy());
service.pay(200);

