Let's start the same way we did with Builder — from the pain, not the pattern.

The problem: behaviour that changes based on conditions
Imagine you're building a navigation app. You need to calculate a route, but the route calculation is different depending on how the user wants to travel — by car, by walking, or by bicycle. A first instinct looks like this:
javaclass Navigator {
    void navigate(String transportMode) {
        if (transportMode.equals("car")) {
            // complex car routing logic
            System.out.println("Navigating by car: use highways...");
        } else if (transportMode.equals("walk")) {
            // complex walking logic
            System.out.println("Navigating on foot: use footpaths...");
        } else if (transportMode.equals("bike")) {
            // complex cycling logic
            System.out.println("Navigating by bike: use cycle lanes...");
        }
    }
}
This feels fine at first. But now think about what happens when the app grows. You need to add public transit. Then ferries. Then express routes. Then toll-free routes. Each addition means you crack open Navigator, add another else if, and risk breaking the existing logic. The class becomes a large, fragile blob of conditionals. Testing it is painful because you can't test one mode without the entire class being present. And every time any routing algorithm changes, the same file gets edited — by multiple developers, causing conflicts.
This is the exact problem the Strategy pattern is designed to solve.

The core idea: extract the varying behaviour into its own family
The insight is simple but powerful: the thing that varies is the algorithm itself. So instead of keeping all algorithms inside one class, you pull each algorithm out into its own separate class, make them all implement a common interface, and then swap them in and out at runtime.
The Navigator doesn't need to know how to navigate by car. It just needs to know that it has some strategy for navigating, and that strategy has a navigate() method it can call. What that strategy actually does internally is entirely its own business.
