The full code, piece by piece
java// ─── Step 1: The Strategy interface ──────────────────────────────
// This is the contract. Every algorithm must implement this.
// The Context only ever talks to this interface — never to the
// concrete classes directly.
interface RouteStrategy {
    void buildRoute(String start, String end);
}


// ─── Step 2: Concrete strategies ─────────────────────────────────
// Each algorithm lives in its own class. They are completely
// independent — changing CarRouteStrategy affects nothing else.

class CarRouteStrategy implements RouteStrategy {
    @Override
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Car route from " + start + " to " + end
            + ": prefer highways, avoid tolls if possible.");
    }
}

class WalkRouteStrategy implements RouteStrategy {
    @Override
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Walking route from " + start + " to " + end
            + ": use footpaths, avoid busy roads.");
    }
}

class BikeRouteStrategy implements RouteStrategy {
    @Override
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Cycling route from " + start + " to " + end
            + ": prefer cycle lanes, avoid steep hills.");
    }
}


// ─── Step 3: The Context ──────────────────────────────────────────
// Navigator holds a reference to a RouteStrategy — just the interface,
// never the concrete type. It delegates the actual work to that strategy.
// It has NO if-else, NO switch. It doesn't care which strategy it holds.

class Navigator {
    // Holds a strategy — type is the interface, not a concrete class
    private RouteStrategy strategy;

    // Strategy is injected via constructor (or can be set later)
    public Navigator(RouteStrategy strategy) {
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    // Allows swapping strategy at runtime — this is a key feature
    public void setStrategy(RouteStrategy strategy) {
        this.strategy = strategy;
    }

    // The context delegates to the strategy — it just calls the interface method.
    // It has no idea whether it's calling CarRouteStrategy or BikeRouteStrategy.
    public void navigate(String start, String end) {
        strategy.buildRoute(start, end);  // pure delegation
    }
}


// ─── Step 4: Client code ──────────────────────────────────────────
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Start with car navigation
        Navigator navigator = new Navigator(new CarRouteStrategy());
        navigator.navigate("Home", "Office");
        // → Car route from Home to Office: prefer highways...

        // User switches to walking mid-session — swap the strategy at runtime
        navigator.setStrategy(new WalkRouteStrategy());
        navigator.navigate("Office", "Restaurant");
        // → Walking route from Office to Restaurant: use footpaths...

        // Switch to bike — same navigator, different behaviour, zero if-else
        navigator.setStrategy(new BikeRouteStrategy());
        navigator.navigate("Restaurant", "Park");
        // → Cycling route from Restaurant to Park: prefer cycle lanes...
    }
}
Notice something important: the Navigator class never changes, no matter how many transport modes you add. Adding a PublicTransitStrategy tomorrow is purely additive — a new file, and one new new call at the composition root. Navigator never even finds out.

The runtime swap — why it matters
One thing videos often gloss over is that the strategy can change at runtime, not just at startup. In the example above, setStrategy() allows the very same navigator object to behave differently mid-execution. This is what makes the pattern genuinely powerful in real applications.
Think about a real scenario: a sorting feature in a data dashboard. When data is small, a simple BubbleSortStrategy is fine. When the dataset crosses a threshold, you programmatically swap to MergeSortStrategy — the calling code doesn't change at all, the behaviour just shifts underneath it.
java// The strategy can even be chosen based on runtime data
RouteStrategy chosen = userPreferences.wantsEcoRoute()
    ? new BikeRouteStrategy()
    : new CarRouteStrategy();

Navigator navigator = new Navigator(chosen);
This is impossible to do cleanly with if-else chains inside the class — the decision about which algorithm and the execution of the algorithm are completely entangled. Strategy separates them.

Adding a new strategy — OCP in full effect
Here is what adding public transit support looks like with the Strategy pattern:
java// New file — that's all. Zero existing files touched.
class PublicTransitStrategy implements RouteStrategy {
    @Override
    public void buildRoute(String start, String end) {
        System.out.println("Transit route from " + start + " to " + end
            + ": use metro line 2, transfer at Central, take bus 47.");
    }
}

// Usage — one new line at call site
navigator.setStrategy(new PublicTransitStrategy());
navigator.navigate("Home", "Airport");
Compare this to the if-else version, where you'd have to open Navigator, find the right place in a growing conditional block, and hope you don't accidentally break any of the other branches. With Strategy, you never touch existing code at all.

The three things Strategy gives you
Eliminates conditionals. Every if (mode == "car") in your context class is a sign that a strategy wants to be born. The pattern converts conditionals into polymorphism.
Independent testability. You can write a unit test for CarRouteStrategy in complete isolation — no need to construct a Navigator, no need to stub out other modes. Each algorithm is a self-contained, independently testable unit.
Runtime flexibility. Because the strategy is just an interface reference, it can be swapped at any point. This is something inheritance can never give you — you can't change a class's parent at runtime.

A confusion worth addressing: Strategy vs Factory Method
Since you've just learnt Factory, you might notice both patterns involve an interface and multiple implementations. The distinction is intent:
Factory is about object creation — it decides which object to instantiate and hides that decision from you. Strategy is about object behaviour — the object already exists, and you're deciding which algorithm it uses. A Factory might actually use Strategy internally (choose which strategy to inject based on config), and that's perfectly natural — the patterns complement each other rather than compete.

