What the interface literally contains
In the navigation example, the Strategy interface looks like this:
javainterface RouteStrategy {
    void buildRoute(String start, String end);
}
That's it. One method. No implementation, no logic, no if-else — just a method signature that says: "whatever you are, you must be able to accept a start point and an end point, and build a route."

What it means — the contract metaphor
The best way to think about a Strategy interface is as a contract. When a class says implements RouteStrategy, it is making a legal promise to the rest of the system: "I guarantee I have a buildRoute(start, end) method, and you can call it on me without knowing anything else about me."
The Navigator (the Context) relies entirely on this promise. It never says if this is a CarRouteStrategy, do this. It just holds a reference typed as RouteStrategy and calls buildRoute(). It trusts the contract, not any specific class.
This is why the interface is sometimes described as a common language between the context and its strategies — it's the one thing they all agree on, the shared vocabulary that lets them work together without being coupled to each other.

What the interface deliberately leaves out
This is where most explanations stop too early. The interface doesn't just define what's in it — it's equally important to understand what it consciously omits.
It says nothing about how the route is built. CarRouteStrategy might query a highway database, calculate fuel costs, and avoid toll roads. WalkRouteStrategy might look up footpath data and prefer shaded routes. BikeRouteStrategy might factor in elevation. All of that complexity is completely hidden behind the interface — the caller doesn't know and doesn't care. This is the principle of encapsulation of behaviour, and the interface is the wall that enforces it.

Why it needs to be narrow
You might wonder: why does the interface only have one method? Why not put more methods in there?
The answer is that the interface should only define the behaviour that the Context actually needs to use. The Navigator needs to ask "build me a route" — so that's what goes in the interface. If you started adding getEstimatedTime(), getFuelCost(), getAlternateRoutes() and so on, you'd be forcing every single strategy to implement all of those, even if a WalkRouteStrategy has no concept of fuel cost. The interface would become a burden rather than a clean contract.
This is actually an expression of a design principle called the Interface Segregation Principle — keep interfaces focused and minimal so that implementors only need to provide what they genuinely offer.
